# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: joe-litterio
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2000 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began in the spring of 2000.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season and concluded with the 2000 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series, held for the fifty fourth time in 2000, consisted of one team from each of eight super regional competitions and was held in Omaha, Nebraska, at Johnny Rosenblatt Stadium as a double-elimination tournament.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] LSU claimed the championship for the fifth time.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] This is a partial list of conference champions from the 2000 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The NCAA sponsored regional and super regional competitions to determine the College World Series participants.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Each of the sixteen regionals consisted of four teams competing in double-elimination tournaments, with the winners advancing to eight best of three Super Regionals.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The winners of each Super Regional advanced to Omaha.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] 29 teams earned automatic bids by winning their conference championship while 35 teams earned at-large selections.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2000 season marked the fifty fourth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series was held in Omaha, Nebraska.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with LSU claiming their fifth championship with a 6–5 win over Stanford in the final.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The **2000 NCAA Division I baseball tournament** was played at the end of the 2000 NCAA Division I baseball season to determine the national champion of college baseball.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The tournament concluded with eight teams competing in the College World Series, a double-elimination tournament in its fifty fourth year.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Sixteen regional competitions were held to determine the participants in the final event, with each winner advancing to a best of three series against another regional champion for the right to play in the College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] Each region was composed of four teams, resulting in 64 teams participating in the tournament at the conclusion of their regular season, and in some cases, after a conference tournament.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The fifty-fourth tournament's champion was LSU, coached by Skip Bertman.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The Most Outstanding Player was Trey Hodges of LSU.
[src:joe-litterio/2000-ncaa-division-i-baseball-tournament] The following players were members of the College World Series All-Tournament Team.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2001 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) began in the spring of 2001.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season and concluded with the 2001 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series, held for the fifty fifth time in 2001, consisted of one team from each of eight super regional competitions and was held in Omaha, Nebraska, at Johnny Rosenblatt Stadium as a double-elimination tournament.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Miami (FL) claimed the championship for the fourth time.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] This is a partial list of conference champions from the 2001 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] 30 teams earned automatic bids by winning their conference championship while 34 teams earned at-large selections.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2001 season marked the fifty fifth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2001-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Miami (FL) claiming their fourth championship with a 12–1 win over Stanford in the final.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2002 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began in January 2002.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2002 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2002 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The College World Series, which consisted of the eight remaining teams in the NCAA tournament, was held in its annual location of Omaha, Nebraska, at Rosenblatt Stadium.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 22, 2002, with the final game of the double-elimination bracket.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Texas defeated South Carolina 12–6 to win its fifth championship.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2002 season marked the fifty sixth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2002-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Texas claiming their fifth championship with a 12–6 win over South Carolina in the final.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2003 NCAA Division I baseball season,** play of college baseball in the United States organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 16, 2003.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2003 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2003 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 23, 2003, with the final game of the best-of-three championship series, the first such championship series used at the College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Rice defeated Stanford two games to one to claim its first championship.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Three programs joined Division I prior to the 2003 season– Gardner-Webb, which had been a provisional member; Savannah State, which had been a Division II independent; and IPFW, which had been a provisional member.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Howard dropped its baseball program following the 2002 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Sacramento State, which had been a member of the Big West Conference, became a Division I independent.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Bowling Green, which had played in the East Division of the Mid-American Conference, moved to the West Division.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2003 season marked the fifty seventh NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2003-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Rice claiming their first championship with a two games to one series win over Stanford in the final.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2004 NCAA Division I baseball season** play of college baseball in the United States, organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 16, 2004.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2004 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2004 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 27, 2004, with the final game of the best of three championship series.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Cal State Fullerton defeated Texas two games to none to claim its fourth championship.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Three programs joined Division I for the 2004 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Dallas Baptist and Northern Colorado joined from Division II, while Utah Valley joined from the NJCAA.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two programs left Division I prior to the start of the season– Drexel, which dropped its varsity baseball program, and Morris Brown, which discontinued its varsity athletics program.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Both the Ohio Valley Conference (OVC) and the Big South Conference (Big South) added two teams entering the season.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The OVC added Jacksonville State and Samford, both from the Atlantic Sun Conference (A-Sun).
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The Big South added Birmingham–Southern, an independent, and VMI, a former Southern Conference (SoCon) member.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] To compensate for these moves, the A-Sun added Lipscomb, an independent, and the SoCon added Elon from the Big South.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two other schools realigned prior to the start of the season.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] UMBC moved from the Northeast Conference to the America East Conference, and Centenary moved from being an independent to the Mid-Continent Conference.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Both the Colonial Athletic Association, which had competed in American and Colonial divisions, and the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference, which had competed in North and South divisions, eliminated their divisional formats.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2004 season marked the fifty eighth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2004-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Cal State Fullerton claiming their fourth championship with a two games to none series win over Texas in the final.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The **2005 NCAA Division I baseball season** play of college baseball in the United States, organized by the National Collegiate Athletic Association (NCAA) at the Division I level, began on January 21, 2005.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The season progressed through the regular season, many conference tournaments and championship series, and concluded with the 2005 NCAA Division I baseball tournament and 2005 College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] It concluded on June 26, 2005, with the final game of the best of three championship series.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Texas defeated Florida two games to none to claim its sixth championship.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Four programs joined Division I for the 2005 season, all of which joined from Division II.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The four new Division I members were Longwood, North Dakota State, South Dakota State, and UC Davis.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Two programs left Division I following the 2004 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Pace, formerly an Independent, dropped to Division II.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Detroit, formerly a member of the Horizon League, discontinued its varsity baseball program.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The Atlantic Coast Conference added two members prior to the 2005 season.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Miami, previously an Independent, and Virginia Tech, previously a member of the Big East Conference, both joined the conference.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] Division I's four new members, Longwood, North Dakota State, South Dakota State, and UC Davis, all became independents.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The 2005 season marked the fifty ninth NCAA baseball tournament, which culminated with the eight team College World Series.
[src:joe-litterio/2005-ncaa-division-i-baseball-season] The eight teams played a double-elimination format, with Texas claiming their sixth championship with a two games to none series win over Florida in the final.
